 of health education campaign designed in partnership with the chinese government to reduce the prevalence of iron deficiency anemia among rural primary school students these campaigns take the form of a notice sent home to parents a single face to face training session at the school and two face to face training sessions at the school respectively results from both our descriptive and multivariate analyses indicate no effect of any of the three training interventions on either hemoglobin levels or anemia prevalence we find that students in the treatment groups experience no statistical change in either of our outcome variables relative to a control group with no intervention we interpret these results as showing the limited effectiveness of health information campaigns and suggest that policymakers look to other more direct solutions for improving health behaviors in developing settings download pdf+ complete modified october 2011 pdf 230_ _information_paper pdf 858.3 kb topics china stanford university all rights reserved 650 723 2300 terms of use copyright complaints rss+ rss xml feeds
